# Project 4 - OCR for Scanned Pharmaceutical Documents

## Overview
- Learned how OCR (Optical Character Recognition) converts images of text into machine-readable text.
- Focused on scanned pharmaceutical Supplier Data Files (SDFs), where normal PDF text extraction does not work.
- Prepared scanned documents for OCR by improving image quality before text recognition.

## Key Concepts

### Why OCR is Needed
- Scanned PDFs contain images instead of selectable text.
- Standard PDF extraction methods like PyMuPDF's `get_text()` return little or no text.
- OCR converts image pixels into readable text.

### Libraries Used
- PyMuPDF (fitz) – Load PDFs and convert pages into images.
- Tesseract OCR – Extract text from scanned images.
- OpenCV – Image preprocessing and enhancement.
- Pillow (PIL) – Display and manipulate images.
- NumPy – Image array processing.

### OCR Preprocessing Pipeline
1. Load scanned PDF.
2. Attempt normal text extraction.
3. Convert PDF page into an image.
4. Convert image to grayscale.
5. Apply adaptive thresholding to improve contrast.
6. Reduce image noise using bilateral filtering.
7. Resize image to improve OCR accuracy.
8. Rotate images when necessary before OCR.

### Image Processing Techniques
- Grayscale conversion
- Adaptive thresholding
- Bilateral filtering
- Image resizing
- Image rotation

## Why Preprocessing Matters
- Improves OCR accuracy.
- Removes background noise.
- Makes faint text easier to recognize.
- Produces cleaner input for downstream document intelligence pipelines.

## Real-World Applications
- Pharmaceutical Supplier Data Files (SDFs)
- Certificates of Analysis
- Compliance documents
- Vendor records
- Batch documentation

